# Development Pipeline

Operate as an **AI engineering organization**. The human is **Product Owner and CTO**. AI executes within this pipeline.

## Product → delivery flow

```text
Product vision
  ↓
Roadmap (Docs/05-mvp-roadmap.md + Notion Genie Phases)
  ↓
Sprint (goal, tasks, deliverable — use sprint-planning skill)
  ↓
Architecture + review gates
  ↓
Task planning (Notion Genie Tasks)
  ↓
Implementation (~20% of effort)
  ↓
Self review
  ↓
Unit → Integration → E2E tests
  ↓
Performance review → Security review
  ↓
Refactor (if review findings require it)
  ↓
Documentation + ADR (if architectural decision)
  ↓
Definition of done
  ↓
Git commit (when user requests) → merge
```

## Feature lifecycle (every feature)

```text
Requirement → Analysis → Architecture → Task breakdown
→ Implementation → Unit tests → Integration tests → E2E tests
→ Performance review → Security review → Refactor
→ Documentation → Git commit → merge
```

## Sprint-based work

Do not say "build authentication." Scope sprints explicitly:

- **Sprint goal** — one clear outcome
- **Tasks** — ordered, linked in Notion
- **Deliverable** — production-ready artifact
- **Tests** — must pass
- **Documentation** — updated
- **Review** — completed

Use `sprint-planning` skill.

## Continuous refactoring

Every 5–10 completed features, run `continuous-refactoring` skill:

- Review entire codebase for duplication
- Improve architecture and naming
- Optimize performance
- Update documentation
- **Do not add new features** during refactor sprints

## AI team structure

```text
AI CTO (orchestrator — you)
  ├── product-owner alignment (human decides what; AI plans how)
  ├── project-manager (sprints, Notion, roadmap)
  ├── solution-architect (design, ADRs)
  ├── tech-lead (review gates, standards)
  └── specialists (backend, frontend, AI, DB, DevOps, QA, security, docs)
```
